<p>ITIL is very good at defining and running services but not as strong on project processes so using a project management framework like PMBOK fixes that issue nicely. Both are poor at
	IT governance. You need to extract the ITIL and PMBOK processes you need to govern out of the frameworks and integrate them into your process. COBIT is great at governance and IT processes in general but
	it is extremely complex and needs a lot of modification to work in small and medium business The Lean Six Sigma approach
	to business issues and requirements focuses more on analysis/problem solving and time management and is open ended 
	but the Define, Measure, Analyze, Improve, Control processes are very useful in the first 3 phases of ITIL. 
	lean six sigma provides less guidance on the implementation and handover processes so PMBOK should be used.</p>
	
	<h2>A High Level Integrated View of an IT Division</h2>
	<p>
		To successfully run an IT division, you must have a sound integrated approach to management.
	</p>

	<p>
